@sahilTakiar while I agree that it would be optimal to automatically upgrade the database, there are a few problems with making it reliable. First, since there is no rollback script if the upgrade fails in the database is an invalid state. Second, on an existing database the upgrade could take large amount of time which would delay the startup of gobblin. Third, many companies strictly control their databases and want to be in charge of when they are upgraded. This would not be possible if we automatically upgraded.

 I would much prefer if the code was backwards compatible with older versions of the database. That way upgrades could happen whenever and new features wouldn't be exposed until the upgrade had been applied. This is outside the scope of the pull request,  which was scoped to improving the performance of the job history database and ensuring the upgrades could be done. 

Alternatively I wouldn't be opposed to having a configurable option to automatically upgrade the database.

@Kaiserchen I agree the `while (!allPutsSucceeded)` block in `Task.processRecord`. I believe the main benefit is that for a single record, a single slow `Fork` will not block other `Fork`s from seeing the record. However, the next record will not be processed, until all `Fork`s have accepted the record.

I'm also ok with removing this logic, it should simplify the code also. 

Removing the timeouts from the `BoundedBlockingRecordQueue` also sounds reasonable.
